into the late 1950s. Drawing on the insights of business, social, and urban historians, and making use of a wide range of documentary sources, Richard Harris shows how the middle-class preference for home ownership first emerged in the 1920s—and how manufacturers, retailers, and the federal government combined to establish the massive home improvement market and a pervasive culture of Do-It-Yourself. Deeply insightful, Building a Market is the carefully crafted history of the emergence and evolution of a home improvement revolution that changed not just American culture but the American landscape as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBuilding materials industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConstruction industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDwellingsxRemodelingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDwellingszUnited StatesxMaintenance and repairxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahome improvement, renovation, construction, remodeling, maintenance, repair, homes, domesticity, design, architecture, middle class, ownership, housing market, do it yourself, diy, culture, nonfiction, history, commerce, capitalism, economics, lowes, ace hardware, building materials, finish carpentry, amateur, flooring, wall treatments, plumbing, electricity, additions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022631766340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226317687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226317687/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 200